      "results": {
        "grok-4.1-fast": {
          "answer": "**The most famous couplet for its line about hopelessness is the opening sher (couplet) itself, which gives the ghazal its title and sets the theme of dashed expectations:**\n\n> Koi ummeed bar nahin aati  \n> Koi soorat nazar nahin aati[^1]\n\n**English translation:**  \n> No hope I have is ever answered,  \n> No way ahead can be uncovered.[^2]\n\nThis refrain of despair (\"nahin aati\" — \"does not come\") echoes through the ghazal's 10 couplets, but the first is iconic for directly evoking hopelessness in love, life, and fate — a hallmark of Ghalib's style in *Diwan-e-Ghalib*.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/115-koi-ummeed-bar-nahin-aati/transliteration/#p-6396af).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/115-koi-ummeed-bar-nahin-aati/translation/#p-92c600).\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/115-koi-ummeed-bar-nahin-aati/translation/).",
