      "results": {
        "grok-4.1-fast": {
          "answer": "The verse you are referring to is the second couplet (sher) of the ghazal, where Ghalib describes building a wall-less house with **no neighbor (humsaya)** and **no guard/door-keeper (pasban)**—terms that evoke solitude free from companionship or intrusion.[^1]\n\n**Translation:**  \nA house I'll build of neither wall nor stone,  \nNo neighbor there, no guard, and be alone.[^1]\n\n**Transliteration:**  \nBe-dar-o-deewar sa ek ghar banaya chahiye  \nKoi humsaya na ho aur pasban koi na ho[^2]\n\n**Original (Urdu):**  \nبے_در_و_دیوار سا اک گھر بنایا چاہیے  \nکوئی ہمسایہ نہ ہو اور پاسباں کوئی نہ ہو[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/168-rahiye-ab-aisi-jagah-chal-kar-jahan-koi-na-ho/translation/#p-09bdfe).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/168-rahiye-ab-aisi-jagah-chal-kar-jahan-koi-na-ho/transliteration/).\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/168-rahiye-ab-aisi-jagah-chal-kar-jahan-koi-na-ho/original/).",
