      "id": "q-0005",
      "category": "citation",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "prompt": "In Iqbal's 'Shikwa', show me the verse where the speaker complains directly to God about the fate of Muslims.",
      "rationale": "Tests retrieval inside Bang-e-Dara Part 3 chapter 20, the famous complaint poem.",
      "expected_works": [
        "allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8"
      ],
      "results": {
        "grok-4.1-fast": {
          "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's *Shikwa* (from *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*), the speaker—representing the Muslim ummah—directly addresses God (referred to as \"O God\" or implied through context) with a lament about their past glories contrasted against their current degradation, disgrace, and loss of worldly favor to non-Muslims/infidel foes.[^1]\n\nOne key opening verse establishing the direct complaint:\n\n> Forgive my tongue, but God, I have a grievance to declare.[^2]\n\nThis builds into explicit grievances about Muslims' fate, such as:\n\n> But all Your blessings fall upon the houses of the foe,  \n> While on the wretched Muslims falls the lightning’s fiery blow.[^3]\n\n> The idols in the temples say, “The Muslims now are gone!”  \n> They celebrate that guardians of the Kaaba have withdrawn.  \n> ...  \n> The unbelievers mock us now—do You feel this or not?  \n> The Creed of Your own Oneness—have You utterly forgot?[^4]\n\n> The outrage is that infidels get nymphs and mansions there,  \n> While for the wretched Muslim, just the promise of a prayer.  \n> ...  \n> Why is the wealth of this world now so scarce for Muslim hands?  \n> ...  \n> We face the taunts of strangers, disgrace, and poverty;  \n> Is this the prize for those who gave their very lives for Thee?[^5]\n\n> The world has now become the friend of those who are not ours,  \n> And for ourselves, a world of dreams is all that now empowers.  \n> We have departed from the stage; others possess its towers.[^6]\n\nThe full poem elaborates this theme throughout, juxtaposing Muslim heroism (e.g., conquering for God's name) with their present subjugation.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 20 \"Shikwa\" ([/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/](https://falsafa-corpus.org/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/)).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., [p-7932bc](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-7932bc).\n\n[^3]: Ibid., [p-20fc7c](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-20fc7c).\n\n[^4]: Ibid., [p-c09121](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-c09121).\n\n[^5]: Ibid., [p-45880c](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-45880c) to [p-d1e7fe](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-d1e7fe).\n\n[^6]: Ibid., [p-bd43b7](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/20-shikwa/translation/#p-bd43b7).",
